Problem 1. Research Writing

  1. In part 1, they used Pearsonâs correlation. The key word âcorrelationâ suggest that they either performed a Pearsonâs correlation test or Spearmanâs rho. Since kg year-1 and km are both continuous variables instead of rankings it is likely Pearsonâs r. In part 2, they used a one-way ANOVA. The key phrase âdifference in averageâ indicates ANOVA which aims to compare the means (averages) of more than one group. The type of ANOVA was determined by the number of groups, the results indicated the comparison of more than three groups which requires a one-way ANOVA.

  2. To add more context to the results, my coworker should provide a Tukeyâs Honestly significant Difference and key ANOVA statistics. It is important to include Tukeyâs HSD because it provides context as to which of the 6 groups were actually different from each other. This is test is important because it prevents Type I errors. Include key ANOVA statistics such as test type, F-value, degrees of freedom, and significance level to strengthen the statistical results. It aids readers ability to interpret data and draw conclusions and it promotes transparency and reduces skeptism, the p-value doesnât tell the whole story so it is important to communicate all statistical results.

  3. ANOVA statistics: We found that there was a significant difference in average nitrogen load (kg year-1) between sources (urban land, atmospheric deposition, fertilizer, waste water treatment, and grasslands) (one-way ANOVa, F(df among groups, df withing groups),p = 0.02, Î± = significance level). Tukeyâs HSD: On Average, urban land tended to have [higher or lower] nitrogen loads (kg year-1) than grasslands ( _ kg year-1 (higher or lower), _ % CI: [x:y] kg year-1) and fertilizer (_ kg year-1 (higher or lower), _ % CI: [x:y] kg year-1 )â¦

Problem 3. Data Analysis

  1. The â1âsâ and â0âsâ in this data set represent occupancy of nest boxes. If âspâ is 1, that indicates that the box is occupied by swift parrots, if not occupied or occupied by a non target speciesâspâ is 0. Of the four occupation options: âspâ, âcsâ, âeâ, and âtmâ each box will only have one â1â and the other three will be â0âsâ

  2. In the context of this study the main difference between Swift Parrots and the other species, Common Starling and Tree Martin, is that Swift Parrots are critically endangered making them at risk to extinction. Providing a safe place to facilitate and encourage the successful breeding on Swift Parrots could be crucial in helping the species population recover.

  3. Defining the year as seasons is important in the context of this study because when the boxes were initially installed in 2016 there were no previous occupant therefore there were more open boxes. However in 2019 many boxes were already occupied by non-target species when Swift Parrots arrive for mating season.

Model number Season Distance to forest edge Description

1 X X Season, Distance to forest edge

#remove all data that is not used in model predictions
nest_boxes_clean <- nest_boxes |>
    clean_names() |> #replacing spaces with underscores
#remove box, box occupant, event ID, and, repeated use
select(!c(box, box_occupant, event_id,repeated_use))
# model 0: null model
model0 <- lm(
  sp ~ 1, # presence of sp as response variable  
  data = nest_boxes_clean) # data frame)

# model 1: all predictors
model1 <- lm(
  sp ~ edge_distance + season, # edge distance and season as predictor
  data = nest_boxes_clean )# data frame)

# model 2: Season
model2 <- lm(
  sp ~ season,#season as predictor
  data = nest_boxes_clean)

# model 3: Distance to forest edge
model3 <- lm(
  sp ~ edge_distance, #edge distance as predictor
  data = nest_boxes_clean)
par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(model0)

 and there are no factor predictors; no plot no. 5

#writing model that predicts occupancy based on edge for each season
nest_ocup_mod <- glm(sp ~ edge_distance + season,
                     data = nest_boxes_clean,
                     family = binomial)
#plotting residuals to look at diagnostics and asses model fit 
plot(simulateResiduals(nest_ocup_mod))
#displaying summary output to look at model coefficients
summary(nest_ocup_mod)

  1. Swift Parrots tend to occupy nest boxes more frequently when those boxes are located closer to the forest edge (see model summary table, part h; and predicted values, part j). With each 1-meter increase in distance from the forest edge, the odds of nest box occupancy decrease (OR = 1.0, 95% CI: [1.00, 1.00], p < 0.001 , Î± = 0.05). At the forest edge (0 m), the probability of occupancy is higher in both seasons, with predicted probabilities of 0.48 (95% CI:[0.33, 0.64]) in 2016 and 0.30 (95% CI:[0.18, 0.44]) in 2019. At 900 m from the forest edge, occupancy probabilities decrease substantially to 0.12 (95% CI:[0.06, 0.24]) in 2016 and 0.06 (95% CI:[0.03, 0.13]) in 2019. This trend suggest that Swift Parrotsâ have a preference for edge habitat, this could be due to factors like food and resource availability.

Problem 4. Affective and Exploratopry Visualizations

  1. The way that the visualizations represent my data is very different. The exploratory visualizations from homework 2 were very simple, just a basic bar graph and linear regression. My affective visualization from homework 3 is a less obvious display of data, it is not interpret-able at first glance like my effective visualizations despite the data showing the same trends. The biggest similarity between my visualizations are the tends in data the trends visualized in my affective visualization are the same trends represented in my exploratory visualizations.The pattern of higher caffeine intake leading to higher productivity is displayed in both visualizations, along with the pattern of more hours of productivity in the library than at home. The only major differences is an increase in variables, my visualizations from homework 2 did not contain any observations from the âlabâ category, but my affective visualization had lots of observations from the âlabâ category showing trends of high productivity.Some of the feedback that I got during the week 9 workshop was to create an ombre effect with my colors that signify caffeine consumption. I attempted to apply this feedback, however since darker colors tend to be longer and lighter colors tend to be longer the data visualization no longer fit the screen in an asymmetric way and no longer showed the variation within my weeks so I decided not to implement this change.
